        legend.position = "top",
        axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        strip.background = element_rect(color="black",
                                        fill="#ffffff"))


```

A two-way repeated measures ANOVA was run with factors: *type of outcomes*
(differential versus non-differential), and *type of task* (social versus non-social). The
dependent variable was amount of correct responses in the first 5 of 12 possible responses, in Stage 3 and differences is shown in Figure 8.
A main effect of *type of outcomes* was found, $F$(`r xp2stats["type_out", "num Df"]`, `r xp2stats["type_out", "den Df"]`) = `r xp2stats["type_out", "approx F"] %>% round(3)`, $p=$ `r xp2stats["type_out", "Pr(>F)"] %>% round(3)`, partial $\eta^2 =$ `r xp2stats["type_out", "eta^2"] %>% round(3)`, with the amount of correct responses being higher for the differential outcomes ($M =$ `r xp2_sum_out["1", "mean"] %>% round(2)`, $SD =$ `r xp2_sum_out["1", "sd"] %>% round(3)` correct responses) than the non-differential outcomes ($M =$ `r xp2_sum_out["2", "mean"] %>% round(3)`, $SD =$ `r xp2_sum_out["2", "sd"] %>% round(3)` correct responses). No significant effect of *type of task* was found, $F$(`r xp2stats["type_task", "num Df"]`, `r xp2stats["type_task", "den Df"]`) = `r xp2stats["type_task", "approx F"] %>% round(3)`, $p =$ `r xp2stats["type_task", "Pr(>F)"] %>% round(3)`, partial $\eta^2 =$ `r xp2stats["type_task", "eta^2"] %>% round(3)` and there was no significant 
two-way interaction between *type of task* and *type of outcomes*, 
$F$(`r xp2stats["type_task:type_out", "num Df"]`, `r xp2stats["type_task:type_out", "den Df"]`) = `r xp2stats["type_task:type_out", "approx F"] %>% round(3)`, $p =$ `r xp2stats["type_task:type_out", "Pr(>F)"] %>% round(3)`, partial $\eta^2 =$ `r xp2stats["type_task:type_out", "eta^2"] %>% round(3)`.


### Stage 2 analysis - EEG activity

```{r eeganalysis, echo=FALSE}

data_eeg <- read.csv("data/exp2_data.csv", sep = ";")

data_eeg %>%                                   # Select summarised eeg (8-12 Hz) data from full dataset
  select(Subject, starts_with("X8")) -> eeg
names(eeg) = sub("........","",names(eeg))

mu_test <- with(eeg, t.test(C_Soc, C_NSoc,     # Perform t-test for mu
                            paired = T, 
                            alternative = "two.sided"))

fpo_test <- with(eeg,                          # Perform t-test for the average of the rest of the electrodes
                 t.test(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_Soc, P_Soc, O_Soc)),
                        rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_NSoc, P_NSoc, O_NSoc)),
                        paired = T, alternative = "two.sided"))

mu_desc <- with(eeg, data.frame(              # Get descriptive stats for mu
  Soc = c(mean(C_Soc, na.rm = T), sd(C_Soc, na.rm = T)),
  NSoc =c(mean(C_NSoc, na.rm = T), sd(C_NSoc, na.rm = T)),
  row.names = c("Mean", "SD")))


fpo_desc <- with(eeg, data.frame(             # Get descriptive stats for the rest
  Soc = c(mean(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_Soc, P_Soc, O_Soc)), na.rm = T),
               sd(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_Soc, P_Soc, O_Soc)), na.rm = T)),
  NSoc =c(mean(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_NSoc, P_NSoc, O_NSoc)), na.rm = T),
               sd(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_NSoc, P_NSoc, O_NSoc)), na.rm = T)),
               row.names = c("Mean", "SD")))

mu_effect <- with(eeg,                       # Get mu effect size
                  cohensD(C_Soc, C_NSoc, 
                          method = 'paired'))

fpo_effect <- with(eeg,                      # Get effect size for the average of the rest
                  cohensD(rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_Soc, P_Soc, O_Soc)),
                          rowMeans(data.frame(Fp_NSoc, P_NSoc, O_NSoc)), 
                          method = 'paired'))


```


A paired-samples *t*-test was used to determine whether there was a significant mean
difference in participants’ mu band power between the social and non-social videos over
electrode C3 and C4. Participants showed an unexpected increase in mu band power when
observing the social videos ($M =$ `r round(mu_desc[1,1], 3)`, $SD =$ `r round(mu_desc[2,1], 3)` 
power spectral density) compared to
the non-social videos ($M =$ `r mu_desc[1,2] %>% round(3)`, $SD =$ `r mu_desc[2,2] %>% round(3)` 
power spectral density), a statistically significant mean increase of 0.29 in power spectral density was found, 95% CI [`r mu_test[["conf.int"]][1] %>% round(3)`, `r mu_test[["conf.int"]][2]%>% round(3)`], $t$( `r mu_test[["parameter"]][["df"]]`) = `r mu_test[["statistic"]][["t"]] %>% round(3)`, $p$ = `r mu_test[["p.value"]] %>% round(3)`, $d =$ `r mu_effect %>% round(3)`.
Furthermore, to potentially explain the unexpected
direction of the mu effect, a paired-samples *t*-test was used to determine whether there
was a significant mean difference between social and non-social videos in 8-12 Hz (alpha
band frequency range) amplitude averaged over the remaining electrodes, that is Fp1,
Fp2, P7, P8, O1 and O2. Participants showed an increase in the alpha band frequency
range when observing the social videos 
($M =$ `r fpo_desc[1,1] %>% round(3)`, $SD =$ `r fpo_desc[2,1] %>% round(3)` 
power spectral density) as compared to the non-social videos 
($M =$  `r fpo_desc[1,2] %>% round(3)`, $SD =$ `r fpo_desc[2,2] %>% round(3)` 
power spectral density), a statistically significant mean increase of `r (fpo_desc[1,1] - fpo_desc[1,2])%>% round(3)`
in power spectral density, 
95% CI [`r fpo_test[["conf.int"]][1]%>% round(3)`, `r fpo_test[["conf.int"]][2]%>% round(3)`], $t$(`r fpo_test[["parameter"]][["df"]]`) = `r fpo_test[["statistic"]][["t"]]%>% round(3)`, $p$ = `r fpo_test[["p.value"]] %>% round(3)`, $d$ = `r fpo_effect %>% round(3)`.

### Subjective report

```{r subrep, echo=FALSE, include=FALSE}

cron_alpha <- psych::alpha(exp2_quest, check.keys = TRUE)$total$std.alpha

```


Questionnaires on a 7-point Likert scale were provided to participants to assess the extent
of perceived emotional engagement in the task and also whether they experienced the
presence of the confederate participant (social condition). Appendix B provides the
results in full for the 14 questions administered and *t*-test statistical differences from the
‘baseline’ score of 4. Due to a relatively low internal consistency 
(Cronbach's alpha = `r round(cron_alpha, 3)`), these results are interpreted cautiously. Admittedly
it would be of interest to factorise the items in the questionnaire and regress the number of correct responses
in Stage 3 on factor scores for "emotional" items. However, due to the low internal consistency and a poor
sampling adequacy ($KMO=$ `r KMO(exp2_quest)[["MSA"]] %>% round(3)`) we could not justify such approach. 

## Discussion

The results indicate that, as for Experiment 1, a transfer of control for differential
outcomes based training in a social context occurs. This conclusion is based on the
significant difference in forced choice performance in the test phase (Stage 3) of the
differential outcomes conditions versus the non-differential outcomes condition where no
interaction effect of sociality (social versus non-social conditions) was found. In this
experiment, therefore, participants appear to have been able to learn from the affective
expression of the confederate the value of the novel stimuli and transfer this knowledge
as well as that of E-R based associations learned in Stage 1 to the test phase Stage 3.
Again, participants, at the beginning of Stage 3, have had no exposure to the particular
SR pairings that are relevant to obtain the rewarding outcomes. The EEG findings, relevant
to providing a measure of perceived social presence in participants, require some
interpretation. The finding of an increase in mu band power was the opposite of that
hypothesized, however, a possible explanation for this might be inadequate separation
from alpha indicated by the subsequent alpha analysis. It is therefore important to
interpret these results in the context of the social versus non-social conditions and what
cognitive and affective resources may have been brought to bear. The video (social versus
non-social) independent variable had no significant effect on the amount of correct
responses, also as expected. The subjective report (questionnaire) findings also lend
support to participants either cognitively or emotionally empathizing with the
confederate. Whilst it was not explicitly asked of participants whether they apprehended
that the confederate was indeed a confederate – for fear of affecting future data collection
– no impressions were given by the participants that they considered the ‘other’
participant to be inauthentic. Expressions of the confederates (particularly the confederate
used in Stage 2 of the Experiment, as opposed to the training phase) did not, therefore,
appear to be perceived as ‘socialized’ (e.g. non-Duchenne smile) or fake.

General Discussion
============

The present article presents work aimed at evaluating whether the differential outcomes
based transfer of control effect^[This concerns transferring knowledge from previous task 
stages to a third stage without the requirement of new learning.] (ToC) as predicted by the
Associative Two-Process theory [@trapold1970expectancies; @urcuioli2005behavioral] could apply
in social contexts. The social contextsexperimentally evaluated how a perceived other’s outcomes
might be inferred: i) through direct presentation of stimulus-outcome contingencies, ii) through
indirect presentation of outcomes as conveyed by the other’s affective facial expression. The main
finding of our investigation was that the ToC effect can apply in social contexts and was robust to
the change in contingencies (i. and ii. above) as manipulated in the two experimental
conditions reported here.

We have considered a hypothesis and explanation for this *social* ToC according to
vicarious value learning [@lowe2016minimalist; @ruff2014neurobiology] whereby through
evaluating another’s rewarding outcomes, the perceiver updates his/her own value
function – effectively putting him/herself in the shoes of the other. This was manipulated
to occur either through direct perception of the other’s (differential) outcomes (as in
Experiment 1), or through cognitive or emotional empathizing [@drimalla2019face] via
affective processing of the facial expression of other (Experiment 2). In the latter case,
facial expressions corresponded to the differential outcomes, or rather reactions to them.

A main source of interest was to consider to what extent the participants viewed the
participating other (confederate) as being present and as the context thereby being
“social”. In Experiment 1 and 2 we evaluated this through the use of questionnaires
whereby participant subjective reporting provided some evidence of vicarious value
learning. The Social Affective-Associative Two Process hypothesis [@lowe2016minimalist]
posits that in non-competitive situations an individual may learn the value function of
another vicariously through emotional contagion as a result of observing the affective
expression of the other. A reinforcement learning model was described that has been
successfully deployed to explain transfer of control (ToC) performance in individual
subjects (pigeons, rats) in non-social settings [@lowe2017affective; @lowe2017affective1].
Although the computational model has not so far been used to model the current data it
is expected that according to the vicarious value learning perspective it should replicate
the qualitative performance of the individual ToC. This would be the case simply because
individuals are hypothesized to use the same value function to valuate stimuli presented
to them as they would stimuli presented to the other. A ToC should not result if a separate
value function for other is represented (e.g. in a competitive context, see @suzuki2012learning, for an example reinforcement learning model).

The task was deliberately set up to require participants to produce fast responses (time
out and negative reward was presented for slow responding). The aim here was to
promote learning by subconscious associative processes rather than by any other such
cognitive strategies. However, we cannot rule out that such cognitive strategies were
being used at least by a subset of the participants some of the time. Participants may have
been using a type of cognitive empathy ([@drimalla2019face]) whereby the affective
expressions of the confederate other were evaluated and understood but not in a manner
that directly tapped into vicarious value learning (e.g. through emotional contagion). 

The uncovering of a social presence signal – mu suppression – as an indicator of mirror neuron
activity would have provided evidence for a vicarious value learning strategy, however
in Experiment 2 the opposite result was found. It is suggested that this effect is a product
of inconsistent set-up of the EEG-headset and that it was not really mu rhythmicity that
was detected at all. @oberman2007human, for example, suggested that their detection of
mu, recorded at C3, Cz and C4, might be contaminated by posterior alpha activity since
the two bands overlap, even though they took effort to control for this. @klimesch2007eeg
proposed that during action observation mu rhythm should desynchronise but that
areas involved in action planning such as the supplementary motor area (SMA), adjacent
to the pre- and primary motor cortex, should exhibit increased synchronisation. Findings
from @muthukumaraswamy2004changes and @muthukumaraswamy2004mu
provide some support for this claim as they recorded 8-12 Hz desynchronizations over
sensory-motor areas, and indeed, a synchronisation of alpha over SMA during action
observation. 

We postulate, therefore, that the synchronisation of mu over C3 and C4 has
to do with the inconsistent set-up of the headset which possibly resulted in the
contamination of alpha synchronisation from SMA consistent with the possibility of
suppression of egocentric activity (self-planning) during perceived other responseoutcome 
events. In the present research increased alpha band power was found in the
social conditions as compared to the non-social (baseline) conditions. An implication of
this is that measuring alpha synchronisation over SMA could constitute a neural signature
for the processing of social stimuli. However, further research, in combination with
simultaneous mu (de)synchronization effects is necessary to be carried out. The presence
of both would provide stronger evidence for the existence of vicarious value learning
according to emotional contagion.

Future study is aimed at testing further the existence of vicarious value learning through
Social Affective-Associative Two Process hypothesis, e.g. in competitive versus 
noncompetitive contexts. We are also interested in using computational models of this
process for synthetic studies, i.e. human-robot interaction (see @lowe2009dual; @lowe2013exploring;
@kiryazov2013role; @alenljung2017user; @andreasson2018affective; @lowe2019vicarious; for examples)
as a further means of apprehending the validity of such
affective-cognitive processing and in the context of ‘minimalist’ joint activity (or joint
action) research [@vesper2010minimal], which focuses on the use of associative mechanisms
to produce intelligent collaborative behaviour.

